      PFOF
   =20
 =20

In general, in the US, if you buy or sell stock through a big retail broker=
age, your broker sends your order to a =E2=80=9Cwholesaler=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0a big electronic market-making firm like Citadel Securities, Virtu=
 Financial Inc. or Jane Street Capital =E2=80=94=C2=A0which takes the other=
 side of the trade, selling you the stock you=E2=80=99re buying or buying t=
he stock you=E2=80=99re selling. The wholesalers want to trade with retail =
orders, because in general retail orders are less=C2=A0risky than orders on=
 the public stock exchanges; they have less =E2=80=9Cadverse selection.=E2=
=80=9D If a market maker is trading on the stock exchange, and it buys 100 =
shares of stock, then there is a decent chance that the seller knows someth=
ing it doesn=E2=80=99t. Perhaps the seller is a clever hedge fund that has =
done lots of clever research and knows that the stock is about to go down; =
if so, the market maker will lose money on the stock it bought. Or perhaps =
the seller is a gigantic pension fund and is going to go on to dump a milli=
on shares and drive down the price; if so, the market maker will also lose =
money on the stock it bought. Or perhaps the seller is an even faster and s=
marter electronic trader than the market maker, and it knows that the stock=
 will go down in the next microsecond, etc.
But if the market maker buys 100 shares directly from a Robinhood Markets I=
nc. customer, then it knows that it is not trading with a big pension fund =
or hedge fund or high-frequency trader. It=E2=80=99s certainly possible tha=
t a Robinhood trader is particularly well informed, or has a ton of stock t=
o sell (or buy) and has broken up that trade into smaller orders, but it is=
 less likely than it is on the stock exchange. So this is a more attractive=
 trade for the market maker.
And so market makers strike deals with retail brokerages to trade with thei=
r order flow. In exchange for this sweet sweet retail order flow, the marke=
t makers give the brokerages two things:
=09
Price improvement:=C2=A0If the lowest offer price for a stock on the stock =
exchange is $10.02, the market maker might sell it to the retail customers =
for a bit less, say $10.017. If the highest bid price is $10.01, the market=
 maker might buy it from retail customers for a bit more, say=C2=A0$10.013.=
 Effectively the wholesaler charges a lower bid/ask spread for less risky o=
rder flow. The retail broker=E2=80=99s customers get the savings.=09
Payment for order flow, or PFOF:=C2=A0The market maker just writes the brok=
erage a check for sending it the order flow. The retail brokerage keeps thi=
s money for itself, though in practice in a competitive market=C2=A0the bro=
kerage might use the money to, for instance, subsidize zero-commission trad=
ing.

This is all terrifically controversial and we talk about it a lot, for inst=
ance  here.
Intuitively,=C2=A0there is a simple one-for-one tradeoff between price impr=
ovement and payment for order flow. If a retail order is worth $1 to a whol=
esaler, it might be willing to pay $1 to trade with that order, but it shou=
ld be indifferent between=C2=A0paying $1 of price improvement to the retail=
 customer, or paying $1 of PFOF to the retail brokerage, or paying $0.60 of=
 price improvement and $0.40 of PFOF, or whatever other split. (In fact the=
re seems to be a  quasi-SEC-endorsed best-practices split of at least 80% p=
rice improvement and at most 20% payment for order flow, though that=E2=80=
=99s not a rule or anything.)=C2=A0
Some retail brokerages seem to make a lot of their money from payment for o=
rder flow. Others make less. Some big retail brokerages do not accept any p=
ayment for order flow at all: They still use this system (routing their ord=
ers to market makers), but they take 100% of the value in the form of price=
 improvement for their customers instead of payments for themselves. Intuit=
ively, you might think that the brokerages that get a lot of PFOF would get=
 worse price improvement.
But, nope! Here is Bill Alpert in Barron=E2=80=99s:

Critics of retail brokers like Robinhood Markets=C2=A0condemn those compani=
es for routing customers=E2=80=99 orders to market makers like Citadel Secu=
rities in exchange for payments. ...
The suspicion is that greater payments to brokers must be offset by less fa=
vorable execution prices. But that isn=E2=80=99t what a new study finds.
In an Aug. 13 working paper, five finance professors analyzed 85,000 stock =
trades they made through five leading retail brokers. They did get signific=
antly different pricing through different brokers for identical orders to b=
uy or sell at the current market price.
But their best pricing came from a broker that takes payment for order flow=
, namely TD Ameritrade, now a unit of Charles Schwab. Fidelity, which takes=
 no order payments, got worse prices on the professors=E2=80=99 trades than=
 did TD Ameritrade. And its prices were no better than those from the E*Tra=
de unit of Morgan Stanley, which does take payments. Robinhood, which used =
revenue from order-flow payments to subsidize the industry=E2=80=99s first =
commission-free trading, delivered middle-of-the-pack pricing. Interactive =
Brokers=C2=A0ranked last in the execution pricing of the professors=E2=80=
=99 orders.

And here is the paper, =E2=80=9CThe =E2=80=98Actual Retail Price=E2=80=99 o=
f Equity Trades,=E2=80=9D by Christopher Schwarz, Brad Barber, Xing Huang, =
Philippe Jorion and Terrance Odean. They opened accounts at five brokerages=
 and placed 85,000 trades in 128 stocks, using the brokerages=E2=80=99 appl=
ication programming interface when possible to trade automatically. They mo=
stly did trades of $100 (rounded to the nearest number of full shares), wit=
h a few $1,000 trades. And they found that:
=09They got better execution than the national best bid or offer available =
on the stock exchange. =E2=80=9CAcross our six brokerage accounts, we calcu=
lated that the average round trip cost ranged from =E2=80=930.07% to =E2=80=
=930.45%; the average price improvement varied from $0.03 to $0.08 per shar=
e.=E2=80=9D That is, on average, when they bought a stock and then sold it =
later in the day, they lost about 0.07% to 0.45% of their money.
  [1]
 If they had traded at the national best bid or offer =E2=80=94=C2=A0the pu=
blicly available benchmark price on the stock exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0they =
would have lost 0.62% of their money.
  [2]
=C2=A0But their retail brokerages routed their orders to wholesalers, who s=
aved them $0.03 to $0.08 per share, or 0.17% to 0.55% of their money.=09But=
 they got systematically different execution quality from different brokera=
ges. Their trades cost on average 0.07% at TD Ameritrade, 0.20% at E*Trade,=
 0.23% at Fidelity, 0.31% at Robinhood,=C2=A00.44% in their Interactive Bro=
kers Pro account (which charges commissions and does not take PFOF), and=C2=
=A00.46% in their Interactive Brokers Lite account (which has no commission=
s and takes PFOF). There was also =E2=80=9Csome variation in the best and w=
orst venues,=E2=80=9D i.e. wholesalers; =E2=80=9CCitadel on average provide=
s the best execution while Two Sigma and UBS have the worst execution, with=
 a maximum range around 3 cents.=E2=80=9D=09And these differences were not =
correlated to how much payment for order flow those brokerages get. The no-=
PFOF accounts did not systematically get better execution than the ones tha=
t took PFOF.

=E2=80=9CThere is no evidence that PFOF harms price execution,=E2=80=9D the=
y say, but I am not sure that is what is interesting here? What is interest=
ing is that some brokerages get better execution than others, and that =E2=
=80=9Cthe dispersion is due to off-exchange wholesalers systematically givi=
ng different execution prices for the same trades to different brokers,=E2=
=80=9D but that it=C2=A0has nothing to do with how much those brokerages pa=
y=C2=A0wholesalers. The same wholesalers execute the same order for the sam=
e number of shares of the same stock at=C2=A0different prices=C2=A0for diff=
erent retail brokerages:

To investigate whether brokers are systematically given different price exe=
cution regardless of venue or stock routing decisions, we obtain specific r=
outing data for every trade for four of our brokers.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 We find=
 that our observed execution differences are largely explained by =E2=80=9C=
broker execution.=E2=80=9D We come to this conclusion by calculating the di=
fference in price executions for=C2=A0matched trades, i.e., the exact same =
trades executed by the same venue for different brokers at the same time. A=
ll the execution differences we observe are explained by this driver. In ad=
dition, broker execution differences are not due to one venue only but are =
systematic across all the venues. =E2=80=A6
In the end, we find that our price differences are due to different brokers=
 getting different execution prices for the exact same trade at the same ve=
nue.=C2=A0

That is, they find that every wholesaler gives (say) Interactive Brokers or=
ders less price improvement than TD Ameritrade orders.=C2=A0Why? They don=
=E2=80=99t say! Weird.
Here are two possible explanations, which are a little bit=C2=A0related to =
each other. One is that retail brokerages are seeking =E2=80=9Cbest executi=
on=E2=80=9D for their customers in a sort of aggregate way.
  [3]
=C2=A0They route their orders to wholesalers not by running an individual a=
uction for each trade, but by examining the wholesalers=E2=80=99 overall pe=
rformance over days or months and sending more orders to wholesalers who pr=
ovide better total price improvement. But the brokers vary in what they are=
 looking for. For instance, one broker=C2=A0might prefer a wholesaler who p=
rovides a lot of price improvement on small orders and less price improveme=
nt on large orders (because its customers mostly do small trades); another =
might prefer one who does better on large orders (because its customers mos=
tly do big trades).=C2=A0
This paper looks at $100 trades, which are pretty small. You could imagine =
a story that goes like: =E2=80=9CTD Ameritrade is the best brokerage for ex=
ecuting=C2=A0small trades, while other brokerages might be better for large=
 trades. But this paper only ranks brokerages on execution of small trades,=
 so it finds that TD Ameritrade is the best.=E2=80=9D
The other explanation has to do with what I said at the beginning, about ad=
verse selection and retail orders being more attractive than institutional =
ones. That is not always and uniformly true. Some retail brokerages have cu=
stomers who are more institutional-like: They are better informed or trade =
larger sizes. A wholesaler who trades with those customers will=C2=A0do wor=
se=C2=A0than a wholesaler who trades with smaller and less-informed retail =
customers. So it will offer them less price improvement. If a brokerage=E2=
=80=99s orders are riskier and less profitable for wholesalers, those order=
s will get less price improvement. The fact that the professors=E2=80=99 In=
teractive Brokers Pro account performed relatively poorly might have someth=
ing to do with who Interactive Brokers Pro is designed for: pros.=C2=A0If y=
ou are a market maker trading with pros, you will charge a higher spread th=
an if you are trading with amateurs.
  [4]

The basic thing that happens in retail stock trading is that wholesalers ar=
e able to segregate the market into institutional orders (on the stock exch=
ange, risky) and retail orders (direct from brokers, less risky), and charg=
e the retail orders less because they are less risky. The implication of th=
is paper might be that they can discriminate more finely: Some retail broke=
rages have riskier orders than others, so they get charged more.
This sort of thing can make people angry. Segregating retail and institutio=
nal orders means that institutional orders get charged more and retail orde=
rs get charged less, which means that effectively your boring conservative =
mutual fund=E2=80=99s trades subsidize some Robinhood gambler=E2=80=99s tra=
ding. And I suppose you have the same problem with discrimination among bro=
kerages.=C2=A0Here is a  Bloomberg News story about this paper:
Extrapolating from the results, they estimate it costs small-time US invest=
ors as much as $34 billion a year, said Christopher Schwarz, the finance pr=
ofessor at the University of California, Irvine who wrote the study along w=
ith four colleagues. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0The overall cost figure is an estimate =
of what investors would save if their orders were executed by the best perf=
orming of the five brokers in the study instead of the fourth best.
But I=E2=80=99m not sure that is the right conclusion? The best-performing =
broker is cheaper=C2=A0because wholesalers can discriminate; they think tha=
t some brokerages=E2=80=99 orders are less risky than others=E2=80=99, so t=
hey charge some brokerages less and others more. If the wholesalers couldn=
=E2=80=99t discriminate =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they gave every brokerage the sam=
e price improvement, or if every retail investor in America read this paper=
 and moved their accounts to TD Ameritrade=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then they wo=
uld have to charge the less-risky investors more to make up for charging th=
e more-risky investors less.

