Texas is taking steps that could cost BlackRock Inc., UBS Group AG and eigh=
t other finance firms business with the state after finding them to be host=
ile to the energy industry.
Glenn Hegar, the Republican state comptroller, on Wednesday named the firms=
 he considers to =E2=80=9Cboycott=E2=80=9D the fossil fuel sector. The move=
 ends roughly six months of suspense that led Texas municipal-bond issuers =
to avoid banks whose status was unclear amid the office=E2=80=99s probe int=
o companies=E2=80=99 energy policies. Governmental entities should use the =
list as a =E2=80=9Cfiltration system=E2=80=9D when entering contracts, Hega=
r said in an interview.=C2=A0

Those firms disagree:

BlackRock, the world=E2=80=99s largest asset manager, said in an emailed st=
atement that the company disagrees with the comptroller=E2=80=99s assessmen=
t.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThis is not a fact-based judgment,=E2=80=9D the statement said. =
=E2=80=9CBlackRock does not boycott fossil fuels -- investing over $100 bil=
lion in Texas energy companies on behalf of our clients proves that. Electe=
d and appointed public officials have a duty to act in the best interests o=
f the people they serve. Politicizing state pension funds, restricting acce=
ss to investments, and impacting the financial returns of retirees is not c=
onsistent with that duty.=E2=80=9D
A spokesperson for UBS said the company also disagrees with the decision. =
=E2=80=9CWe provided their office with extensive information on our policie=
s and practices, demonstrating that UBS does not boycott energy companies e=
ven under a broad interpretation of Texas law,=E2=80=9D the statement said.=
=C2=A0

The basic issue here is that if you are an investment firm, and you decide =
not to invest in some particular oil company, Texas will send you a threate=
ning letter saying =E2=80=9Cwe won=E2=80=99t do business with people who bo=
ycott fossil fuels.=E2=80=9D And you will say =E2=80=9Cno, no boycott, we d=
idn=E2=80=99t invest in that company because we thought that the climate-re=
lated risks to its business were very high, so as a pure valuation matter w=
e thought it was a bad investment.=E2=80=9D And Texas will say =E2=80=9Cno =
we think it=E2=80=99s because you don=E2=80=99t like oil companies.=E2=80=
=9D And you will send them a bunch of data and investing memos and policy s=
tatements and legal analyses about how really you are only considering clim=
ate change as a financial matter, and they won=E2=80=99t believe you.=C2=A0=
We talked about this sort of thing yesterday.  I wrote:
A certain amount of the ESG fight will take the form of broad public statem=
ents of principles. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0But a lot of it will take the form (and =
has already taken the form) of fact-intensive debates about particular inve=
stment decisions. Some investment manager will say =E2=80=9Cwe are underwei=
ght oil and gas companies because we are concerned about the financial impa=
ct of climate transition risk,=E2=80=9D and some state regulator will say =
=E2=80=9Cwe think it=E2=80=99s actually because you are environmentalists,=
=E2=80=9D and the investment manager will say =E2=80=9Cno here is our inves=
tment model that considers environmental risk as a factor in assessing risk=
 and returns,=E2=80=9D and the regulator will say =E2=80=9Cwe think that yo=
u are using inappropriately long investment horizons and imprudently weight=
ing this risk in your calculation,=E2=80=9D and the manager will provide su=
pport for its view, and they=E2=80=99ll go back and forth. Every financial =
decision can also become a political argument. It seems exhausting.
It still does.

