      APE voting
   =20
 =20

We   talked yesterday about AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s weird=
 APE preferred-stock units, which are meant to be a close substitute for AM=
C=E2=80=99s common stock but which currently trade at about a 25% discount.=
 (APE closed at $7.13 yesterday, AMC at $9.58.) Specifically we talked abou=
t an arbitrage trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0put on by Jim Chanos among others =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0of buying APE, shorting AMC, and hoping that that discount will=
 close. The discount will close, for instance, if AMC gets shareholder appr=
oval to issue more common stock, at which point the APEs will automatically=
 convert into common.  Here=E2=80=99s Chanos:
"Functionally, the two securities are the same. And I'd guess the apes [i.e=
., AMC=E2=80=99s enthusiastic retail shareholders] will be putting pressure=
 on [AMC Chief Executive Officer Adam]=C2=A0Aron, if the discount continues=
, to make it freely convertable sooner rather than later," Chanos told CNBC=
.
I expressed some doubt about that, because the thing about apes is that the=
y don=E2=80=99t vote. AMC has tried before to get shareholder approval to i=
ssue more common stock, but it couldn=E2=80=99t. It would need a majority o=
f all its outstanding shares to vote to approve that, and that=E2=80=99s ha=
rd when 80% of its shares are held by retail investors. I=C2=A0wrote:
AMC stock is mostly held by retail investors, and it is widely assumed that=
 retail shareholders mostly don=E2=80=99t vote their stock. And in fact if =
you look at the results of AMC=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shareholder voting this year=
=C2=A0=E2=80=94 on routine matters like electing directors and approving ex=
ecutive pay =E2=80=94 only about 145 million shares (out of 516 million) we=
re actually voted. So it might just be impossible for AMC to get a majority=
 of its shares to vote for=C2=A0anything.
A couple of people pointed out that the APEs help to=C2=A0solve=C2=A0that p=
roblem. The APE shares have the same voting rights as the common stock, mea=
ning that AMC has effectively doubled its voting stock from 516 million to =
1.03 billion shares. Day One, this doesn=E2=80=99t matter: Each AMC shareho=
lder went from holding one common share=C2=A0to holding one common share an=
d one APE, with the same voting rights; if those shareholders weren=E2=80=
=99t likely to vote their one share before=C2=A0then they are no more likel=
y to vote their two shares now. But over time, you might expect that to cha=
nge. Low-information low-involvement retail shareholders might be more like=
ly to buy AMC common stock (it=E2=80=99s normal, it=E2=80=99s common stock,=
 it has the ticker symbol =E2=80=9CAMC=E2=80=9D), while the APEs might migr=
ate into the hands of specialized APE enthusiasts and=C2=A0arbitrageurs lik=
e Jim Chanos.
And then at some point AMC goes out to get a shareholder vote on converting=
 the APE shares into common stock, and:
=09A lot of the APE shares are held by professional arbitrageurs like Chano=
s who are=C2=A0really engaged=C2=A0with the idea of converting their shares=
 into common =E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s their whole trade thesis =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and so will definitely vote; and=09Even with the APE shares that a=
re held by low-engagement retail shareholders, it is an easier pitch for th=
e company to say =E2=80=9Clook your APE shares are worth $7 and AMC stock i=
s worth $9.50, so if you check a box on this form you=E2=80=99ll get a free=
 $2.50=E2=80=9D
  [5]
=C2=A0than it was to say =E2=80=9Cplease vote for us to be able to issue mo=
re shares to do unspecified corporate finance things.=E2=80=9D

So the APEs are a way to give voting rights to people who will be naturally=
 incentivized to vote for what AMC=E2=80=99s management wants, which is mor=
e common stock. This is by no means a certainty =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you only =
get 20% of AMC common shareholders to vote to authorize more shares, then y=
ou need to get 80% of APE holders to vote for it =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it help=
s.

