<tr>
<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow, back on Monday.</em></p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PFOF</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, in the US, if you buy or sell stoc=
k through a big retail brokerage, your broker sends your order to a =E2=80=
=9Cwholesaler=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0a big electronic market-making firm l=
ike Citadel Securities, Virtu Financial Inc. or Jane Street Capital =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0which takes the other side of the trade, selling you the stock you=
=E2=80=99re buying or buying the stock you=E2=80=99re selling. The wholesal=
ers want to trade with retail orders, because in general retail orders are =
less=C2=A0<em>risky </em>than orders on the public stock exchanges; they ha=
ve less =E2=80=9Cadverse selection.=E2=80=9D If a market maker is trading o=
n the stock exchange, and it buys 100 shares of stock, then there is a dece=
nt chance that the seller knows something it doesn=E2=80=99t. Perhaps the s=
eller is a clever hedge fund that has done lots of clever research and know=
s that the stock is about to go down; if so, the market maker will lose mon=
ey on the stock it bought. Or perhaps the seller is a gigantic pension fund=
 and is going to go on to dump a million shares and drive down the price; i=
f so, the market maker will also lose money on the stock it bought. Or perh=
aps the seller is an even faster and smarter electronic trader than the mar=
ket maker, and it knows that the stock will go down in the next microsecond=
, etc.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if the market maker buys 100 shares direct=
ly from a Robinhood Markets Inc. customer, then it knows that it is not tra=
ding with a big pension fund or hedge fund or high-frequency trader. It=E2=
=80=99s certainly possible that a Robinhood trader is particularly well inf=
ormed, or has a ton of stock to sell (or buy) and has broken up that trade =
into smaller orders, but it is less likely than it is on the stock exchange=
. So this is a more attractive trade for the market maker.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so market makers strike deals with retail =
brokerages to trade with their order flow. In exchange for this sweet sweet=
 retail order flow, the market makers give the brokerages two things:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Price improvement:=C2=A0</em>If the lowest offer price for a stock on t=
he stock exchange is $10.02, the market maker might sell it to the retail c=
ustomers for a bit less, say $10.017. If the highest bid price is $10.01, t=
he market maker might buy it from retail customers for a bit more, say=C2=
=A0$10.013. Effectively the wholesaler charges a lower bid/ask spread for l=
ess risky order flow. The retail broker=E2=80=99s customers get the savings=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Payment for order flow</em>, or PFOF:<em>=C2=A0</em>The market maker ju=
st writes the brokerage a check for sending it the order flow. The retail b=
rokerage keeps this money for itself, though in practice in a competitive m=
arket=C2=A0the brokerage might use the money to, for instance, subsidize ze=
ro-commission trading.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all terrifically controversial and we =
talk about it a lot, for instance <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9=
uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDUvcm9iaW5ob29kLWdhbWVzdG9wLXNhZ2EtcHJlc3N1cmVzLX=
BheW1lbnQtZm9yLW9yZGVyLWZsb3c_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZ=
Gl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODI1JnV0bV9jYW1w=
YWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2eba92fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLi=
nk" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> here</a>.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively,=C2=A0there is a simple one-for-on=
e tradeoff between price improvement and payment for order flow. If a retai=
l order is worth $1 to a wholesaler, it might be willing to pay $1 to trade=
 with that order, but it should be indifferent between=C2=A0paying $1 of pr=
ice improvement to the retail customer, or paying $1 of PFOF to the retail =
brokerage, or paying $0.60 of price improvement and $0.40 of PFOF, or whate=
ver other split. (In fact there seems to be a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDcvdGhlLWlwby1tYXJrZXQtd2FzLXRvby1nb2=
9kP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZ=
T1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc9daaf0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> quasi-SEC-endorsed best-practices sp=
lit</a> of at least 80% price improvement and at most 20% payment for order=
 flow, though that=E2=80=99s not a rule or anything.)=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some retail brokerages seem to make a lot of t=
heir money from payment for order flow. Others make less. Some big retail b=
rokerages do not accept any payment for order flow at all: They still use t=
his system (routing their orders to market makers), but they take 100% of t=
he value in the form of price improvement for their customers instead of pa=
yments for themselves. Intuitively, you might think that the brokerages tha=
t get a lot of PFOF would get worse price improvement.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, nope! Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFycm9ucy5jb=
20vYXJ0aWNsZXMvcGF5bWVudC1mb3Itb3JkZXItZmxvdy1zZWMtNTE2NjEyODA3MzI_bW9kPVNl=
YXJjaHJlc3VsdHM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB549b30ab" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Bill Alpert in B=
arron=E2=80=99s</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Critics of retail brokers like Robinhood Marke=
ts=C2=A0condemn those companies for routing customers=E2=80=99 orders to ma=
rket makers like Citadel Securities in exchange for payments. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The suspicion is that greater payments to brok=
ers must be offset by less favorable execution prices. But that isn=E2=80=
=99t what a new study finds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an Aug. 13 working paper, five finance prof=
essors analyzed 85,000 stock trades they made through five leading retail b=
rokers. They did get significantly different pricing through different brok=
ers for identical orders to buy or sell at the current market price.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But their best pricing came from a broker that=
 takes payment for order flow, namely TD Ameritrade, now a unit of Charles =
Schwab. Fidelity, which takes no order payments, got worse prices on the pr=
ofessors=E2=80=99 trades than did TD Ameritrade. And its prices were no bet=
ter than those from the E*Trade unit of Morgan Stanley, which does take pay=
ments. Robinhood, which used revenue from order-flow payments to subsidize =
the industry=E2=80=99s first commission-free trading, delivered middle-of-t=
he-pack pricing. Interactive Brokers=C2=A0ranked last in the execution pric=
ing of the professors=E2=80=99 orders.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here is the paper, =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBl=
cnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQxODkyMzk/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cB4bcb6fb4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">The =E2=80=98Actual Retail Price=E2=80=99 o=
f Equity Trades</a>,=E2=80=9D by Christopher Schwarz, Brad Barber, Xing Hua=
ng, Philippe Jorion and Terrance Odean. They opened accounts at five broker=
ages and placed 85,000 trades in 128 stocks, using the brokerages=E2=80=99 =
application programming interface when possible to trade automatically. The=
y mostly did trades of $100 (rounded to the nearest number of full shares),=
 with a few $1,000 trades. And they found that:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They got better execution than the na=
tional best bid or offer available on the stock exchange. =E2=80=9CAcross o=
ur six brokerage accounts, we calculated that the average round trip cost r=
anged from =E2=80=930.07% to =E2=80=930.45%; the average price improvement =
varied from $0.03 to $0.08 per share.=E2=80=9D That is, on average, when th=
ey bought a stock and then sold it later in the day, they lost about 0.07% =
to 0.45% of their money.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> If they had traded at the national best bid or offer =E2=80=94=C2=A0th=
e publicly available benchmark price on the stock exchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
hey would have lost 0.62% of their money.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But their retail brokerages routed their orders to wholesalers, w=
ho saved them $0.03 to $0.08 per share, or 0.17% to 0.55% of their money.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But they got systematically <em>dif=
ferent</em> execution quality from different brokerages. Their trades cost =
on average 0.07% at TD Ameritrade, 0.20% at E*Trade, 0.23% at Fidelity, 0.3=
1% at Robinhood,=C2=A00.44% in their Interactive Brokers Pro account (which=
 charges commissions and does not take PFOF), and=C2=A00.46% in their Inter=
active Brokers Lite account (which has no commissions and takes PFOF). Ther=
e was also =E2=80=9Csome variation in the best and worst venues,=E2=80=9D i=
.e. wholesalers; =E2=80=9CCitadel on average provides the best execution wh=
ile Two Sigma and UBS have the worst execution, with a maximum range around=
 3 cents.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">And these diffe=
rences were not correlated to how much payment for order flow those brokera=
ges get. The no-PFOF accounts did not systematically get better execution t=
han the ones that took PFOF.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere is no evidence that PFOF harms =
price execution,=E2=80=9D they say, but I am not sure that is what is inter=
esting here? What is interesting is that some brokerages get better executi=
on than others, and that =E2=80=9Cthe dispersion is due to off-exchange who=
lesalers systematically giving different execution prices for the same trad=
es to different brokers,=E2=80=9D but that it=C2=A0has nothing to do with h=
ow much those brokerages pay=C2=A0wholesalers. The same wholesalers execute=
 the same order for the same number of shares of the same stock at=C2=A0<em=
>different prices=C2=A0</em>for different retail brokerages:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To investigate whether brokers are systematica=
lly given different price execution regardless of venue or stock routing de=
cisions, we obtain specific routing data for every trade for four of our br=
okers.=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 We find that our observed execution differences are l=
argely explained by =E2=80=9Cbroker execution.=E2=80=9D We come to this con=
clusion by calculating the difference in price executions for=C2=A0matched =
trades, i.e., the exact same trades executed by the same venue for differen=
t brokers at the same time. All the execution differences we observe are ex=
plained by this driver. In addition, broker execution differences are not d=
ue to one venue only but are systematic across all the venues. =E2=80=A6</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the end, we find that our price differences=
 are due to different brokers getting different execution prices for the ex=
act same trade at the same venue.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, they find that every wholesaler gives=
 (say) Interactive Brokers orders less price improvement than TD Ameritrade=
 orders.=C2=A0Why? They don=E2=80=99t say! Weird.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are two possible explanations, which are =
a little bit=C2=A0related to each other. One is that retail brokerages are =
seeking =E2=80=9Cbest execution=E2=80=9D for their customers in a sort of a=
ggregate way.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0They route their orders to wholesalers not by running an individu=
al auction for each trade, but by examining the wholesalers=E2=80=99 overal=
l performance over days or months and sending more orders to wholesalers wh=
o provide better total price improvement. But the brokers vary in what they=
 are looking for. For instance, one broker=C2=A0might prefer a wholesaler w=
ho provides a lot of price improvement on small orders and less price impro=
vement on large orders (because its customers mostly do small trades); anot=
her might prefer one who does better on large orders (because its customers=
 mostly do big trades).=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This paper looks at $100 trades, which are pre=
tty small. You could imagine a story that goes like: =E2=80=9CTD Ameritrade=
 is the best brokerage for executing=C2=A0small trades, while other brokera=
ges might be better for large trades. But this paper only ranks brokerages =
on execution of small trades, so it finds that TD Ameritrade is the best.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other explanation has to do with what I sa=
id at the beginning, about adverse selection and retail orders being more a=
ttractive than institutional ones. That is not always and uniformly true. S=
ome retail brokerages have customers who are more institutional-like: They =
are better informed or trade larger sizes. A wholesaler who trades with tho=
se customers will=C2=A0<em>do worse=C2=A0</em>than a wholesaler who trades =
with smaller and less-informed retail customers. So it will offer them less=
 price improvement. If a brokerage=E2=80=99s orders are riskier and less pr=
ofitable for wholesalers, those orders will get less price improvement. The=
 fact that the professors=E2=80=99 Interactive Brokers Pro account performe=
d relatively poorly might have something to do with who Interactive Brokers=
 Pro is designed for: pros.=C2=A0If you are a market maker trading with pro=
s, you will charge a higher spread than if you are trading with amateurs.<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic thing that happens in retail stock t=
rading is that wholesalers are able to segregate the market into institutio=
nal orders (on the stock exchange, risky) and retail orders (direct from br=
okers, less risky), and charge the retail orders less because they are less=
 risky. The implication of this paper might be that they can discriminate m=
ore finely: Some retail brokerages have riskier orders than others, so they=
 get charged more.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This sort of thing can make people angry. Segr=
egating retail and institutional orders means that institutional orders get=
 charged more and retail orders get charged less, which means that effectiv=
ely your boring conservative mutual fund=E2=80=99s trades subsidize some Ro=
binhood gambler=E2=80=99s trading. And I suppose you have the same problem =
with discrimination among brokerages.=C2=A0Here is a <a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjIvaGlkZGVuLXByaWNlLW9mLW5vLWZlZS1=
0cmFkaW5nLTM0LWJpbGxpb24tYS15ZWFyLXN0dWR5LXNheXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyNTIyX01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jIwODI1JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB19173ff7" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Bloomberg News story</a> about this paper:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Extrapolating from the results, th=
ey estimate it costs small-time US investors as much as $34 billion a year,=
 said Christopher Schwarz, the finance professor at the University of Calif=
ornia, Irvine who wrote the study along with four colleagues. =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0The overall cost figure is an estimate of what investors would save if t=
heir orders were executed by the best performing of the five brokers in the=
 study instead of the fourth best.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I=E2=80=99m not sure that is the right con=
clusion? The best-performing broker is cheaper=C2=A0<em>because wholesalers=
 can discriminate</em>; they think that some brokerages=E2=80=99 orders are=
 less risky than others=E2=80=99, so they charge some brokerages less and o=
thers more. If the wholesalers couldn=E2=80=99t discriminate =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0if they gave every brokerage the same price improvement, or if every ret=
ail investor in America read this paper and moved their accounts to TD Amer=
itrade=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then they would have to charge the less-risky in=
vestors more to make up for charging the more-risky investors less.</p>
