<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Whistle-blowers</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to run the US Securities and Exchange =
Commission would be that you have a bunch of enforcement lawyers, and they =
look for fraud, and if they find fraud the SEC collects a big fine, and the=
n the SEC lawyer who brought the case collects 30% of the fine, personally,=
 as a bonus.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This approach would have some advantages. The =
SEC routinely extracts nine-digit fines =E2=80=94 last month Morgan Stanley=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDctMTQvbW9yZ2Fu=
LXN0YW5sZXktbWlzdXNlLW9mLXBlcnNvbmFsLWRldmljZXMtd2lsbC1jb3N0LTIwMC1taWxsaW9=
uP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB9a52b8eb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  paid $200 million</a> because some o=
f its bankers sent each other text messages =E2=80=94=C2=A0and if SEC enfor=
cement lawyers routinely got paid $60 million bonuses, then the SEC would a=
ttract some very talented and motivated enforcement lawyers, who would be v=
ery good at extracting fines. This would bring in a lot of money to the US =
government, and might also do a lot to deter securities fraud.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But on balance I think this approach would be =
bad? If the SEC=E2=80=99s lawyers got a cut of the fines they extracted, th=
ey would have incentives mainly=C2=A0to extract really big fines, which is=
=C2=A0<em>part=C2=A0</em>of the SEC=E2=80=99s job, but not all or even most=
 of it. The SEC also has to, like, write good rules to encourage capital fo=
rmation, and shut down scammers who are doing a lot of harm but who don=E2=
=80=99t have the money to pay nine-digit fines. Occasionally it even has to=
 investigate some behavior and decide =E2=80=9Cyou know what, this is actua=
lly okay, we don=E2=80=99t need to extract a fine for this.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A prize-money-driven SEC would underweight=C2=
=A0all of those things and focus mainly=C2=A0on extracting big fines from b=
ig banks. It would be more interested in clear-cut but low-impact misbehavi=
or (texting on personal phones!) by deep-pocketed repeat-player institution=
s=C2=A0than in harmful but complicated and novel misbehavior by new entrant=
s (Ponzi schemes in decentralized finance!). It would de-prioritize rule-wr=
iting and emphasize <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMjItMDItMTUveW91LWdldC10aGUtY3J5cHRvLXJ1bGVzLXlvdS1wYXktZm9yP2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDA4MjUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDgyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB9f375f53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;">  regulation by enforcement</a>, which is=C2=A0<em>=
like=C2=A0</em>rule-writing except that you get to extract a big fine for m=
aking new rules.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, this is not the way that the SEC is actua=
lly run. SEC lawyers are paid government salaries and don=E2=80=99t get a c=
ut of the fines they bring in. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZWMtd2=
hpc3RsZWJsb3dlci1hd2FyZHMtcHJvZ3JhbS1taWdodC1oYXZlLWEtcmV2b2x2aW5nLWRvb3Itc=
HJvYmxlbS1zdHVkeS1zYXlzLTExNjYxNDE5ODAx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB507d996b" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> On the other hand</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Over the past several years, the Securities an=
d Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s whistleblower awards program has been champ=
ioned by lawyers and politicians for offering powerful incentives to tipste=
rs to come to the regulator with evidence of wrongdoing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A new study, however, finds that almost a quar=
ter of the SEC=E2=80=99s whistleblower awards have gone to law firms with a=
ttorneys who have close connections to the regulator, potentially deterring=
 other whistleblowers from coming forward. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Using SEC data from awards issued between 2012=
 and 2020 that was obtained through the Freedom of Information Act, the stu=
dy shows that about 23% of awards in the database=E2=80=94or 30=E2=80=94wen=
t to law firms with at least one attorney who was a former SEC official, hi=
ghlighting the potential benefits that this group=E2=80=99s connections mig=
ht have. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Jordan Thomas, an attorney who helped establis=
h the SEC whistleblower program and now at law firm SEC Whistleblower Advoc=
ates PLLC, is =E2=80=9Ca single dominant =E2=80=98revolver,=E2=80=99=E2=80=
=9D according to the study. Mr. Thomas, during his time working for law fir=
m Labaton Sucharow LLP, was responsible for 10 awards in the study=E2=80=99=
s database, accounting for about 20% of all the dollars awarded in the stud=
y, at about $152.6 million, the study said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the paper, by Alexander Platt, titled =
=E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.=
269571/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lk=
PTQxMTIzOTg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd9664fb3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> The Whistleblower I=
ndustrial Complex</a>.=E2=80=9D From the abstract:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The upshot is that the SEC and CFT=
C have effectively privatized the tip-sifting function that is at the core =
of the [whistle-blower programs]. Private lawyers have likely extracted hun=
dreds of millions of dollars in fees and expenses from these programs, with=
 a disproportionate share going to a concentrated group of well-connected, =
repeat players.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked about Jordan Thomas =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the lawyer who designed the whistleblower program at the SEC and then=
 left to be one of its main beneficiaries=C2=A0=E2=80=94 before; <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28846378.269571/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDEtMTgvYmxhY2tyb2NrLXN=
0aWxsLWxpa2VzLWNhcGl0YWxpc20_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgyNTIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZG=
l1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwODI1JnV0bV9jYW1wY=
Wlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB23e29323" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  I wrote</a=
>: =E2=80=9CThis is a good trade =E2=80=94 build a spigot of government mon=
ey and plant yourself in front of it.=E2=80=9D If you currently work at the=
 SEC, I suppose you have incentives to increase the flow out of the spigot =
so that one day you too can plant yourself in front of it.</p>
