8524a319a23cB5f1d5a3a" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">shareholder voti=
ng this year</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=94 on routine matters like electing directors =
and approving executive pay =E2=80=94 only about 145 million shares (out of=
 516 million) were actually voted. So it might just be impossible for AMC t=
o get a majority of its shares to vote for=C2=A0<em>anything</em>.</p></blo=
ckquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A couple of people pointed out that the APEs h=
elp to=C2=A0<em>solve=C2=A0</em>that problem. The APE shares have the same =
voting rights as the common stock, meaning that AMC has effectively doubled=
 its voting stock from 516 million to 1.03 billion shares. Day One, this do=
esn=E2=80=99t matter: Each AMC shareholder went from holding one common sha=
re=C2=A0to holding one common share and one APE, with the same voting right=
s; if those shareholders weren=E2=80=99t likely to vote their one share bef=
ore=C2=A0then they are no more likely to vote their two shares now. But ove=
r time, you might expect that to change. Low-information low-involvement re=
tail shareholders might be more likely to buy AMC common stock (it=E2=80=99=
s normal, it=E2=80=99s common stock, it has the ticker symbol =E2=80=9CAMC=
=E2=80=9D), while the APEs might migrate into the hands of specialized APE =
enthusiasts and=C2=A0arbitrageurs like Jim Chanos.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then at some point AMC goes out to get a s=
hareholder vote on converting the APE shares into common stock, and:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A lot of the APE shares are held by p=
rofessional arbitrageurs like Chanos who are=C2=A0<em>really engaged=C2=A0<=
/em>with the idea of converting their shares into common =E2=80=94=C2=A0tha=
t=E2=80=99s their whole trade thesis =E2=80=94=C2=A0and so will definitely =
vote; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Even with the APE shares=
 that are held by low-engagement retail shareholders, it is an easier pitch=
 for the company to say =E2=80=9Clook your APE shares are worth $7 and AMC =
stock is worth $9.50, so if you check a box on this form you=E2=80=99ll get=
 a free $2.50=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0than it was to say =E2=80=9Cplease vote for us to be able to issu=
e more shares to do unspecified corporate finance things.=E2=80=9D</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the APEs are a way to give voting rights to=
 people who will be naturally incentivized to vote for what AMC=E2=80=99s m=
anagement wants, which is more common stock. This is by no means a certaint=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you only get 20% of AMC common shareholders to vote to =
authorize more shares, then you need to get 80% of APE holders to vote for =
it =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it helps.</p>
